{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_hoh_ver01/data/sn87093220/0020029046A/1914020601/0057.xml":{"full_text":"TWENTY-EIGHTH YEAR\nFORMER BLUNDER\nCAUSES TROUBLE\nMayor France Opposes The\nPayment of Local Damages\nFrom The General Fund\nTERRACE HEIGHTS MIXUP\nSeveral Contracts Awarded\nBy City Council. Fill Dist\nrict No. 2 Held Up\nA blunder of the city in the im\nprovement of Terrace Heights streets\nenlivened the city council meeting\nWednesday night, and bids fair to\ninvolve the city in costly litgation\nbefore the matter is settled. Owing\nto the grades several suits for dam\nages are in sight, and the council\npassed an ordinance creating a spec\nial improvement district, embracing\nthe property affected, which should\nbo assessed to cover such damages.\nFraser moved to recind the ordi\nnance, to which Pearsall objected,\nraising a point of order that Fraser,\nbeing an interested party, was dis\nqualified to vote. The vote stood\nseven to five to recind, and Mayor\nFrance held that a two-thirds Vote\nwould be necessary to recind th?\nordinance, and unhesitantly stated\nthat he was and would be opposed to\nsaddling any cost of improving this\ndistriot on the general fund, and an\nnounced that he would veto the\nordinance upon its passage. It will\nrequire a two-thirds vote to pass th?\nordinance over the veto. Mayor\nFrance explained where he stood on\nthe special assessment proposition.\nHe supplimented his remarks with:\n\"I understand some of you fellows\nwant me to quit. Well, let me tell\nyou, if the public signify this de\nsire, no election will be needed to\nremove me. I will step down and\nout. I live up there In Terrace\nHeights and have been burdened\nwith taxes. I favored the special\nassessment in meeting the condemna\ntion costs, feeling the amount each\nwould have to bear would be small.\nAs to drawing on the general fund,\nwhy it is about depleted now and\nyou councllmen will have to discount\nyour salary warrants if it gets much\nlower. We will fight this proposi\nton to the finish.\"\nArgument alternated from paying\nthe dr. mages out of the general pub\nlic purse to taxing the cost of the\nproperty directly benefited. Council\nman Pearsall said if this one claim\nwas allowed out of the general fund\nthere would be a dozen or more\nclaims filed this week and the city\nwould face a serious financial situ\nation.\nEdwnrd Kelley was awarded the\ncontract for supplying the city with\nweed. The committee's recommen\ndation that the petition for the ex\ntention of B street be denied, was\nadopted. Alex Swanson, J. P. Carl\nson and C. F. Jensen submitted bids\nfor removing the city garbage. The\nbids were referred.\nBids for the city printing were\nopened as follows: Grays Harbor\nPost, 5 cents for first insertion: I\ncents each subsequent insertion,\ncopies of 25 ordinances for each one\npublished free of charge; Aberdeen\nWorld, 4 cents first insertion, 4\ncents each subsequent insertion,\ncopies of 25 ordinances for each one\npublished at 1 cent a copy. The bids\nwere referred.\nThe bonding company for the Spo\nkane Dredging Construction com\npany will be notified to see to it\nthe contractors finish the work in\nFill District No. 2 according to agree\nment. Work has now stopped pend\ning a suit against Fairbanks, Morse\nii Co. for $100,000 brought by the\ncontractors for alleged breach of\nwarranty, claiming the dredge failes\nto deliver the goods as promised. The\ncity holds bonds in the sum of $00.-\n000 for faithful execution of the\ncontract.\nCONVICTED OF ROBBERY\nJury Finds John Dew Guilty Aftc\nBeing Out Over 18 Hours. Rec\nommends Him to Clemency\nMONTESANO, Feb. s.\u2014After be\ning out more than IS hours, the jur>\nin the trial of John Dew. for robbery\nof a house on North river, returnee;\na verdict of guilty yesterday morn\ning and recommended the prisoner\nto the mercy of the court.\nAlong witl) their verdict the jury\nsubmitted a long preamble in whcih\nthey said they thought Dew was no'\na menace to society: that his crime\nMas due to the evils of intoxicating\nliquor and wicked associates; and\nrecommending that the court give\nliim the least possible sentenee.\nABERDEEN HERALD\nASSESSMENT OF\nTIMBER LANDS\nCounty Assessor Wiley and\nTimber Land Owners De\ncide on Equitable Plan\nTO ADOPT BASIS TRACT\nThe Get-together Plan of\nAssessor Wiley Seems\nProductive of Results\nMontesano, Feb. 5. \u2014Quite a few of\nthe owners of large tracts of timber\nin the county accepted the invitation\nof Assessor R. A. Wiley, and met\nwith that official yesterday to dis\ncuss a fair method of proceedure for\nthe coming assessment of timber\nlands. The Weyerhaueser Timber\nCo., the largest holder of timber in\nChehalis county, and which is yet.\nwithholding a large proportion of last\nyear's taxes, was not represented.\nAmong those present were: Mark\nReed, of the Simpson Logging Co..\nAlex Poison, of the Poison Bros. Log\nging Co.; P. R. Hogan, of the Olympic\nLand Co.; E. R. Palmer, of the Pitgot\nMill Co.; the Rainier Investment Co.\nand the Port Blakely Mill Co.; T. C.\nSoul.e of the Stearns Lumber\nShingle Co.: A. P. Sprague, of the\nCarlisle-Pennel Co.: A. L. Flewelling,\nof the Milwaukee Land Co.: Eugene\nPrance, representing himself and\nothers; W.' R. Alack, representing\nhimself and the Slade company; E. 13.\nDowning, of.W. E. Boeing Co., and\nO. O. Orth.\nThe meeting was called for 10\no'clock, a. m\u201e but was postponed until\nafter lunch, owing to the small num\nber present. Mark Reed was chosen\nchairman, and he and the assessor\nspent more than an hour going over\nthe rolls to compare values in the\nvarious sections of the county.\nAgree on Plan.\nAfter discussing the subject until\n4 o'clock, a majority of the timber\nowners and Assessor Wiley agreed\non the following suggestions to gov\nern the assessments on timber lands:\nFirst: Taking township 17, range\n8; townships 17 and 18, range 9, and\ntownships 17 and 18, range 10, as\na basis tract where timber should\nbe valued at its highest, the valuation\nshall be reduced two cents for every\nmile back in any direction, in fixing\nassessable value. The townships\nnamed for base townships are those\nfronting on or intersected by the low\ner Chehalis river and the Grays Har\nbor.\nSecond: Quality of timber \u2014that\nu, ri-id\" \u2014to be based on the cruis\ners' reports now cn file in the as\nsessor's office.\nE. B. Palmer, representing the I'u\nget Mill Co., the Rainier Investment\nCo., and the Port Blakely Mill Co.,\namong which companies are most of\nthe timber holdings in the base dis\ntrict selected, made very positive ob\njections to the first proposal and\nasked \u2666hat it be understood that he\nwas not voting and not taking any\nfurther action in the meeting.\nW. B. Mack objected and voted\n\"no\" on the second motion. His ob\njections were that the present cruise\nestimates on grades was entirely too\nindefinite.\nIn replying to that objection Alex\nPoison, who fathered both motions,\nsaid:\n\"You may cruise the timber of the\ncounty until doomsday and we who\nown timber will never agree that it\nis all properly graded or cruised, no\nmore than the logger and the mil!\nman \u2014no more than Mack and I will\never agree on the scaling of logs.\"\nUP TO BOND COMPANY\nCommittee of City Council on Fill\nDistrict No. 2, Puts Issue Up\nto the Surety Bonds\nAt the city hall last evening a com\nmittee of councilnien met and consid\nered the legal phases of the improve\nment in fill district No. 2, as it re\nlated to the Spokane Paving ft Con\nstruction company, contractor for the\nfill, which has abandoned work be\ncsluse of alleged faulty machinery, a\nsuit against the Fairbanks-Morse com\npany for $100,000 begun by the con\ntractors is now pending.\nThe committee brought out the $60.-\n000 bond furnished by the contrac\ntors. which guarantees fulfillment of\nthe contract within a specified time,\nand it was the decision o\u00a3 the com\nmittee to collect the bond in accord\nance with the agreement\nIt is the understanding the bond\ning company will join hands with its\nclient in the damage action against\nthe company, which, it is claimed,\nsold a dredger that failed to do as\nguaranteed.\nEIGHT J'AGES\nPROSPERITY IS\nON THE WAY\nUnion Pacific Railway System\nPlaces Large Order For\nNew Freight Cars\nSEATTLE, Feb. 5. \u2014An indication\nof the rapid return of prosperity and\npublic confidence came last Friday\nin the announcement of officials of\nthe Union Pacific railroad system\nthat this line has just let contracts\nfor the building of 6,000 freight cars\nat a cost of between $5,500,000 and\n$6,000,000, for delivery beginning the\nmiddle of April and as rapidly there\nafter as the builders can turn them\nout.\nNot only does this immense order\nbear on the return of general pros\nperity, but It wll mean much to the\nlumbermen of the Pacific Northwest,\nsince the greater number of these\ncars will be of wood, and the lumber\nmanufacturers of Western Washing\nton will of necessity be called upon\nto supply most of the lumber.\nOf this rolling stock, 4,000 will be\nthe double-sheep boxcar of 100,000\npounds capacity, 400 will be stock\ncars of the same type as heretofore\nused and have a capacity of 80.00U\npounds each, while 600 of the cars\nwill be of all-steel, exclusively, for\nautomobile use, of 100,000 pounds\ncapacity and fifty feet long inside.\nAll the boxcars will have the steel\nunderframe.\nThe Union Pacific system, which\nincludes all of the Oregon-Washing\nton Railroad Navagation Company\nand the Oregon Shore Line, is the\nfirst of the big railroad systems to\nexpress its confidence as to the\nfuture conditions of the country.\nBIG RED APPLES TO\nADVERTISE APPLE DAY\nA very practical method of adver\ntising the \"big red apple\" and also\nthat Wednesday was \"Apple Day\" lias\nbeen adopted by the Commercial\nClub, Fruit Growers' association and\nCounty Horticultural union of North\nYakima. It is in the form of a largo\nred apple mailed to members and\nofficers of commercial bodies,to per\nsonal friends and to newspapers. The\napples are inclosed in corrugated\npasteboard boxes, together yith lit\nerature descriptive of the fruit in\ndustry, and the outside of the box\ncarries prominent labels of an ad\nvertising nature.\nFEDERAL JURORS\nThe following citizens of Chehalis\ncounty have been drawn to serve, on\nthe jury in the federal court at Ta\ncoma, for the term commencing\nMarch 10: Aberdeen \u2014C. M. Weath\nerwax. R. A. Wiley and J. J. Carney.\nHoquiam\u2014.T. L. Tiaer, C. 13. Crippen.\nRobt. Durney, W. C. Gregg, H. E.\nShanneberger and W. C. Scuneman.\nMontesano \u2014Claude Nutter. Oakville\n\u2014G. T. Taylor.\nPlease mention The Herald when\ndealing with advertisers.\nbEMI-WEEKLY\nABERDEEN, WASHINGTON FRIDAY, FEBRUARY G, 1914\nCUTTING THEM DOWN.\nCITY ELECTIONS\nUNINTERESTING\nGenera] Apathy Appears To\nBe In the Saddle as to\nComing Elections\nLIST OF FILINGS MADE\nTomorrow Is Last Day To\nFile, and Some Surprises\nMay Be In Store\nThe interest being manifested in\nthe coming city primary elections,\nwhich will be held March 10, seems\nto be confied to two classes, the can\ndidates and those having some special\ninterest which they expect to serve.\nThe attitude of the public is not at\nall complimentary to the civic pride\nof Aberdeen, although the condition\nmay change after tomorrow, which is\nthe last day on which filings for can\ndidates may be made. It is rather\nexpected that some surprising nom\ninations will be made this afternoon\nand tomorrow, which may alter the\ncomplexion of things as they appear\nat this writing.\nUp to this morning the following\nfilings had been made for the va\nrious positions.\nFor Treasurer\u2014T. H. Hill, the well\nknown accountant: Chas. P. Blvth, the\npresent deputy treasurer and Dr. ,T.\nA. Mapes, the equally well known\nmedico real estate mm.\nFor City Clerk\u2014Peter F. Clark has\nno opposition for the place he has\nheld for so man years.\nFor police judge it seems to lie\nbetween Glenn R. Snider, the present\nincumbent and Ira A. Gardner.\nIn the first ward, J. ,T. Ryan, the\nwell known and generally esteemed\nproprietor of the Grays Harbor Boiler\nWorks, is opposed by E. C. McKnight\nand Mrs. Rose Manley.\nIn the Second. E. E. Wieland, so\ncialist, present member, is a candi\ndate for re-election, and he is opnosed\nby Harry O'Dell; the pioneer clothing\nman, W. R. Meade stahle foreman at\nthe Wilson mill and Mrs. Caroline\nWiley.\nJ. W. Fraser, in the Third ward is\nopposed for re-election by John O'Hnre\nand in the fourth. Dan Pearsall. pres\nent incumbent had met no opposition\nno to this morning, although it Is a\ncommon rumor that he will be. oppos\ned by ,T. M. Powes. if not others.\nPresent Councilman Morck. in the\nfifth is opposed by J. D. Walker, of\nthe Creech Walker Construction\nCo.. and in the Sixth. George Stn'd\ning is the onlv candidate filing so far.\nalthough there are rumors of several\nmore before tomorrow evening.\nFARMER A BANKRUPT\nMONTESANO. Feb. s.\u2014Wm. T.\nLang, a farmer living near Montpsano.\nlias filed a voluntary petition in bank\nruptcy In which he gives his llablli\nties as $1400 and his assets as noth\ning. Most of the creditors are Mon\ntpsano people.\nCandidates So Far\nMacauiey in New York World\nELKS SMOKER\nBIG SUCCESS\nAthletic Stunts, Fine Music\nAnd Story Telling Pass\nPleasant Evening\nThe smoker given by the Elks\nlodge last night was a hummer, and\nreflected credit on Col. Jim Bowes\nand his able coadjutors on the com\nmittee of arrangements. About 250\nmembers were present, and there was\nsomething amusing doing from 9:00\nto 11:30. Nobody got weary as there\nwere no waits, and the various stunts\nwere loudly encored. A 12-piece or\nchestra supplied the music, and the\nstory-telling proposition was a sure\nhit.\nDr. G. E. Chamberlain presided,\nand gained a reputation for apt wit\nthat will last the balance of his life,\nin fact he can no fbnger pose as the\nmatter of fact M. D. His rr'nutation\nas a wit has been esta'i*' '>ed. he\ncan't get away from it anymore.\nThe Athletic stunts were good. Cap\ntain Dick Ultican and Nick Randich\nled off with a four-round bout that\ndid both credit inasmuch as the de\ncision was a draw.\nThe main boxing event was that of\nTom Morgan, of Seattle, and Chi Pres\nton of Hoqulam. It was a beautiful\nboxing match of six rounds In which\nMorgan was declared winner.\nThe most interesting of events wa?\nthat of story-telling. In the course of\nwhich certain tales were told that\nwere real classic. Among the story j\ntellers whose efforts did much to e>i-,\nliven the evening's proceedings, were\nGeorge Thompson. Tom Shields. Alex-\nPoison, W. 13. Mack, Goodbar Jones. 1\nDan Bowes and A. L. Remllnger.\nINDIAN PRISONER GIVEN\nCHANCE TO SEE DYING SON\nHOQUIAM, Feb. 6. \u2014Fred Pope, the\nQuiniault Indian, who killed two mem\nbers of the Indian police at Taholah\nseveral years ago, and who is now\nserving a sentence at McNeils isl\nand penitentiary for murder, was ex\npected to be taken through Hoquiam\nyesterday on his way to the Indian\ntown, his former home, to see his\nson Chester, who is dying of quick\nconsumption.\nPope was taken to Taholah under\nspecial guard for the sole purpose of\nseeing liis stricken child. This is one\nof the very few cases on record\nwhere a prisoner sent up for nuirder\nis allowed to leave the penitentiarv\nespecially to be taken on trip of the\nlength of this one, for any case, even\nthe last illness of a close relative.\nGAVE LIQUOR TO INDIAN\nHOQUIAM, Feb. 6. \u2014Harry Soper.\n1 aged about 35 years, arrested by Pa\ntrolman Toliver Wednesday while Riv\ning liquor to an Indian girl, was re\nmoved to Montesano yesterday. H\u00b0\nagreed to plead guilty and an in for\nrelation will be filed against him to\nday by the county attorney.\nThe Herald tells It all.\nBIDS ASKED FOR\nWISHKAH ROAD\nCounty Commissioners Call\nFor Bid For Permanent\nHighway Up Wishkah Valley\nWILL APPRAISE MILLS\nCist of Right of Way to Be\nPaid For Out of Road Dist\nrict Funds Hereafter\nMONTESANO, Feb. s.\u2014The boarl\nof county commissioners finished a\ntwo-day session yesterday afternoon\nafter awarding the contract for the\nextension of the North river road to\nthe Pacific county line to Holmlund\nJohnson for clearing, grubbing and\ngrading at about $3,735; for plank\ning to Robert Carl.\nIn awarding this contract, the board\nadopted the rule that the cost of\nright of way shall be paid out of the\nfunds of the district in which the\nproposed road lies and the auditor was\ndirected to draw a warrant for R.\nCarl for $100, on Road District No.\nfor right of way for the road.\nWill Appraise Mills\nThe mills of Chehalis county will\nbe appraised, for the county, by the\nGeneral Appraisal company of Seat\ntle at a cost of $3,800 for this year,\nand 20 per cent yearly for renewing\nthe appraisal for a term of five years.\nThe contract, though not yet signed,\nwas agreed upon yesterday and a\nwire was sent to Seattle ordering\nthe appraisers to begin work at once.\nThis is the first county in the\nstate to undertake anything of this\nsort. The appraisal company hopes\nthrough Chehalis' example to get\nKing county and Pierce. The work\nis to be finished by May 28. The\nassessor had several copies of ap\npraisals of various mills last year\nwhen the board of equalization was\nin session. They were secured from\nInsurance officials in Seattle. How\never, it is argued that a few ap\npraisals are of no value so long as\nnot all are on file and (or this year\nit s proposed to have all of them.\nThe appraisal company agrees to\nsupport its appraisals in court if it\nbecomes necessary.\nThe Withkah Read\nThe auditor was directed to adv*\"\ntise for bids for the improvement\nunder the provisic'\" Perman\nent Highway Act of 1911, the follow\ning section of road: Beginning at\na point on the Wishkah rover road at\nthe northerly corporate limits of the\ncity of Aberdeen, near the south\nwest corner of the southeast quarter\nof Section 33-18-9, and running thence\nnortherly along said Wishkah river\nroad a distance of 5.6 miles to a\npoint in the southeast quarter of Sec\ntion 10-18-9. The improvement will\nconsist in clearing, grubbing, regrad\ning, placing of culverts and of sur\nfacing with gravel.\nFor the clearing, grubbing, regrad\ning and placing of culverts on the G\nN. Thomas county road from Station\n0-00 to corner section 16, 17, 20 and\n21, Tp. 17 N. of R. 7 West.\nThe treasurer was directed to ad\nvertise for sale Block C, Carney\nWoods Addition to Elma. and to\nstrike from the rolls Block 14, Ho\nquiam Add., Aberdeen, and Lots 1,\n2 and 3, Block 10, Pacific Beach for\nthe year 1912.\nE. D. Kellerman was engaged to\nregulate the clock system of the\ncourt house, at 75 cents per hour for\ntme engaged.\nThe county treasurer presented hi*\nreport to the board for the month:\nending December 31, 1913. The board\nproceeded to check same and found\nas follows:\nCash on hand Dec. 1, 1913. .$306,940.37\nReceipts during month 37,248.27\nDisb'nits. during month.. 57.987.31\nBal. on hand Jan. 1, 1914.. 286,201.33\nFINE MAN AND WIPE\nHeavy fines were imposed on Mr.\nand Mrs. Herbert Winney upon their\nconviction in police court Tuesday\nevening of conducting a disorderly\nhouse. Each were fined $30 by Judge\nSnider, who admonished them to con\nduct their home more in keeping with\nthe dignity of the city in the future.\nThe charge against Mrs. T. S. Mc-\nGlauflin and C. Johnson was dismiss\ned. D. Baker, also arrested in the\npolice raid, forfeited his bail of $23.\nThe Winneys have been haled up by\nthe police four times.\nAll the news all the time in the 1\nHerald.\nCHAMBER IS\nREORGANIZED\nNew Organization Is Dffected\nWith Much Enthusiasm\nTuesday Evening\nFOR EFFECTIVE WORK\nNew By-Laws Adapted For\nBetter Work. Plans For\nComing Year Outlined\nThe mmeting of the Chamber of\nCommerce Tuesday evening, at Hotel\nWashington, resulted in the com\nplete reorganization of that body and\nthe adoption of a new set of by-laws.\nThe meeting was attended by nearly\n100 representative citizens of Aber\ndeen, and its tone was most opto\nmistic.\nThe new by-laws were adopted\nwithout a dissenting vote, and the\naddressses all indicated a willingness\nto pull together for Aberdeen and\nGrays Harbor, and a recognition that\nthis and next years were to epochal\nin the North Pacific Coast.\nPresident Mumaw appointed the\nfollowing 12 directors, who are auth\norized to meet and select officers for\nthe coming yenr:\nW. B. Mack, A. L. Davenport, E. C.\nFincli, L. H. Burnett, Carl Weather\nwax, P A. Bertrand, S. K. Bowes,\nG. P. Halferty, F. C. Wilcox. E. A.\nMorck, J. A. Hood and J. W. Parks.\n\nThe New By-Laws.\nThe new by-laws contain several\ndistinct innovations, the chief of\nwhich is the placing of a large\namount of the administrative and\nlegislative work of the Chamber in\nthe hands of an executive committee\ncomposed of from 25 to 50 members\nto be appointed by the president.\nThe idea of an executive commit\ntee was developed as means of secur\ning quick action and widening the\nscope of the work to be carried on by\nthe Chamber. The executive commit\ntee is to be appointed by the presi\ndent within 30 days after his elec\ntion from among the business men of\nthe city. This committee is given\nfull power to transact any business\nwhich the Chamber may lawfully car\nry on under its articles of incorpora\ntion and in every such case may bind\nthe Chamber by its actions This\ncommittee will also determine the\nsalaries of the officers and employes\nof the Chamber and may call for re\nports from them at any time. Its\npowers allow it to act for the Cham\nber in any action whatsoever, except\nthat of election of officers. Amend\nments before being voted upon must\nbe submitted for the consideration\nof the executive committee.\nI The new committee must not be\ncomposed of less than 25 or more\nthan 50 members, the exact number\nto be determined and appointed by\nthe president of the Chamber. This\n1 committee is empowered to perfect\nits own organization and is expected\nto elect a chairman and secretary.\nMeetings of the executive committee\nare to be held monthly and special\nmeetings may be called at the will of\nthe chairman. At the regular meet\ning of the committee a majority of\nthose present will constitute a quor\num, while at the special gatherings\nthere must be 10 members in at\ntendance to make the work done\nbinding.\nThe dues of both resident and non\nresident members have been placed\nat $6 a year, payable quarterly and\nin advance Dues for corporation\nmembers are placed at $12 and are\npayable quarterly and in advance.\nWhen any person or corporation shall\nallow his or its dues to be two conse\ncutive quarters in arrears they may\nbe dropped from membership.\nThe officers under the new organ\nization are the same as under the old\nI \u2014president, vice president, secretary,\ntreasurer and 12 members of a board\nof directors are to be elected at the\nj annual meeting of the Chamber when\nI the president will appoint a nomin\nj ating committee of five to nominate\nj men for the positions on the board.\n|If the Chamber should so vote as\nmany names aB 18 may be submitted.\nI The other officers of the Chamber\nshall be elccted by the board of dir\nectors from among the active mem\nbers of the Chamber. All officers\nshall hold office for one year.\n$344,188.64\n$344,188.64\nPIONEERS MEMORIAL\nj The special committee of the Aber\ndeen Pioneer's Association have se\nj lected Sunday, March 1, for the Mem\norial Day of the association, and\nmemorial services will be held that\nday in the First Congregational\nchurch.\nNUMBER 36\nDirectors Appointed.\nDues Reasonable","height":"28872","width":"21404"}}
